[2] Liberia: "Respect their death"
Date: 20 Dec 2015
Source: Front Page Africa Online [edited]
http://www.frontpageafricaonline.com/index.php/news/7038-respect-their-death-am-dogloitti-dean-tells-liberian-president

Christiana Scotland is the wife of Dr Thomas Scotland, one of the 5 doctors who died during the outbreak of Ebola. Currently, she has 4 children -- all males -- in high school but disclosed that she is faced with the constraints of paying their tuition. Though she is a university graduate, she can't seek a job, as she breastfeeds her 8 month old baby, and cash is hard to come by in order to supplement the breast milk he feeds on. She has called for support to families who lost their spouses during the outbreak of the deadly Ebola virus.

Dr Thomas Scotland was born on 20 Dec 1975. A graduate of the AM Dogloitti College of Medicine, he died on 18 Oct 2014 at a local ETU when he contracted the virus. Several students dressed in black, white and purple gathered at the auditorium of the AM Dogloitti College to memorialize fallen doctors and a medical student who died to save Liberia from Ebola during the peak of the crises.

Some of those remembered include Dr Samuel Muhumuza Mutooro of Uganda, Dr John Taban Dada of Uganda, who died on 9 Oct 2014 and a professor of the Medical College, Dr Samuel Brisbane, an instructor of the Medical College Department of Internal Medicine, Dr Abraham Saah Borbor who died 24 Aug 2014 and Malikee Siryon, a 5th-year medical student of the A M Dogloitti College who died on 18 Dec 2014...

[byline: Bettie K Johnson-Mbayo <betty.johnson@frontpageafricaonline.com>]

