[4] Deficiencies of MSF Ebola triage system
Date: 18 Dec 2015
Source: CIDRAP [edited]
http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2015/12/news-scan-dec-18-2015

The criteria that Medecins Sans Frontieres (MSF; Doctors without Borders) use in triaging West Africa Ebola patients resulted in more than a 3rd of patients falsely testing positive, and the guidance needs to be revised, a study yesterday [17 Dec 2015] in Eurosurveillance concluded.

MSF researchers and local public health officials analyzed data on 433 Ebola patients admitted into MSF's Ebola management center in Kailahun, Sierra Leone, from 1 Jul 1 to 30 Sep 2014. MSF uses 2 triage categories for suspected patients --"suspect" and "highly suspect" -- placing each type of patient into a separate ward.

The investigators found that 276 of patients (64 per cent) were true-positive admissions and 157 (36.3 per cent) were false-positive admissions, meaning they tested positive for the disease when they did not have it and would be exposed to a risk of Ebola infection when placed in a ward with patients who were actually infected.

The positive predictive value for receiving a positive laboratory result after being placed in the highly suspect ward was 76 per cent, and the corresponding negative predictive value was 54 per cent. Sensitivity of the protocol (the proportion of patients with the disease who test positive) was 70 per cent, and specificity (proportion without the disease who test negative) was 61 per cent. Ultimately, 254 (59 per cent) of admissions were classified as highly suspect, with the remaining 179 (41 per cent) as suspect.

The authors conclude, "The current triage system should be changed. Whenever possible, patients should be accommodated in single compartments pending laboratory confirmation. Furthermore, the initial triage step on whether or not to admit a patient in the 1st place must be improved. "What is ultimately needed is a point-of-care EBOV diagnostic test that is reliable, accurate, robust, mobile, affordable, easy to use outside strict biosafety protocols, providing results with quick turnaround time."

