[6] Prevention, vaccine, research, funding

Prevention
-----
21 Dec 2015 Liberia: celebrating a milestone in Liberia: closing an Ebola Treatment Unit
https://www.pciglobal.org/closing-ebola-treatment-unit/
[Liberia has closed its Ebola Treatment Unit (ETU) in Ganta, Nimba County where the director for Project Concern International (PCI) Liberia's country director, Jolene Mullins, Dr Teweldebrhan Abrha (chief of party) and the team have spent the last year in this area mobilizing a team of health professionals to stop the Ebola virus disease (EVD) outbreaks in Liberia. According to director Jolene, "It's a bittersweet celebration as we say goodbye to many members of our medical team who have fought Ebola since the early days and have become an important part of the PCI family."]

21 Dec 2015 Sierra Leone: Enhanced entry airport screening for Ebola to end for travelers from Sierra Leone to the United States
http://www.cdc.gov/media/releases/2015/s1221-airport-screening.html
[On 7 Nov 2015 the World Health Organization (WHO) declared Sierra Leone free of Ebola virus transmission. This date marked 42 days (two 21-day incubation periods) after the last known patient with Ebola tested negative twice for Ebola. On 22 Dec 2015, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) and the Department of Homeland Security (DHS) will remove Sierra Leone from the list of nations affected by Ebola that are subject to enhanced visa and port-of-entry screening.

Travelers leaving Sierra Leone will still require outbound screening measures, and the United States (USA) will continue to support Sierra Leone's Ebola virus disease (EVD) prevention and detection measures, including at its primary international airport. Outbound travelers are still encouraged to monitor their health for 21 days after leaving Sierra Leone and to contact their local health departments or seek healthcare if they develop symptoms consistent with EVD.]

22 Dec 2015 USA: CDC provides Delaware with guidelines on how to prepare for Ebola cases
http://news.delaware.gov/2015/12/22/ebola-preparation-cdc-provides-delaware-guidance
[New cases very unlikely in the state, according to health officials. In partnership with the Division of Public Health (DPH), the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) recently visited Delaware to offer assistance to DPH, Christiana Care Health System's Wilmington Hospital, and Saint Francis Healthcare on their readiness to identify, diagnose, and treat patients suspected of having Ebola or other emerging infectious diseases.]

21 Dec 2015 USA: Exaggerations about Ebola 2014
http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/article/2015/dec/21/look-back-lie-year
[In 2014, there were just 2 Ebola-related deaths in the United States, yet fear of the disease stretched to every corner of the country, stoked by exaggerated claims from politicians and pundits. They said, wrongly, that Ebola was easy to catch, that illegal immigrants may be carrying the virus across the southern border, that it was all part of a government or corporate conspiracy. The false claims distorted the debate about a serious public health issue and edged the nation toward panic. In all, PolitiFact and PunditFact rated 16 separate Ebola claims as Mostly False, False or Pants on Fire, so we chose this collection as our 2014 Lie of the Year.]

*******
Vaccine
----
21 Dec 2015: Sierra Leone ends Ebola vaccine study
http://makonitimes.com/2015/12/21/sierra-leone-ends-ebola-vaccine-study/
[According to Dr Mohammed Samai, the chief investigator in the joint trial that involved the United States CDC, who spoke on Mon 21 Dec 2015, Sierra Leone has shut down its Ebola vaccine study over a year after it started. Dr. Samai also said the trial conducted at the main Connaught Hospital in Freetown had enrolled nearly 9000 participants but that only about 8500 people were vaccinated. Dr Samai (who is also the provost of the medical hospital) also said, except from the normal vaccine-related side effects, there were no serious side effects discovered as a result of the trial. In addition, the study has equipped the university to the extent it can now handle any future similar situations.

Date: 23 Dec 2015 USA: WHO to review Merck's investigational Ebola vaccine for emergency use assessment and listing (EUAL)
http://pipelinereview.com/index.php/2015122360001/Vaccines/World-Health-Organization-to-Review-Mercks-Investigational-Ebola-Vaccine-for-Emergency-Use-Assessment-and-Listing.html
[The EUAL process is designed to expedite the availability of vaccines needed for public health emergencies such as another outbreak of Ebola. The procedure is intended to assist United Nations' procurement agencies and member states on the acceptability of using a vaccine candidate in an emergency-use setting. EUAL designation is not prequalification by WHO, but rather is a special procedure implemented when there is an outbreak of a disease with high rates of morbidity and/or mortality and a lack of treatment and/or prevention options. In such instances, WHO may recommend making a vaccine available for a limited time, while further clinical trial data are being gathered for formal regulatory agency review by a national regulatory authority.

Research
----
[Ebola virus and bats have been waging a molecular battle for survival that may have started at least 25 million years ago, according to a study led by researchers at Albert Einstein College of Medicine, the University of Colorado-Boulder (CU-Boulder) and the US Army Medical Research Institute of Infectious Diseases (USAMRIID) that was published online today in the journal eLife. The findings shed light on the biological factors that determine which bat species may harbor the virus between outbreaks in humans and how bats may transmit the virus to people.] [This is a very technical article. - Mod.JW]

22 Dec 2015 Liberia: Ebola mystery: Did a woman who tested negative infect her family?
http://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2015/12/22/460700289/ebola-mystery-did-a-mom-who-tested-negative-infect-her-family
[Dr Mosoka Fallah, a Harvard-trained epidemiologist in Liberia, who specializes in tracing the origins of Ebola cases, is trying to determine how a father and 2 of his children became infected with Ebola virus in mid-November [2015] -- more than 2 months after Liberia had been declared Ebola-free. In the latest Ebola virus disease (EVD) outbreak in Liberia (now resolved) there are questions that still need to be answered about the origins and causes of the outbreak. These questions include who was the actual source of the latest outbreak of EVD in Liberia, and can a pregnant woman who survived EVD once still harbor ebolavirus in immune-privileged areas of the body can infect their sexual partners if the woman's immune system is compromised.]
[The article is well worth reading. - Mod.JW]

Funding
----
22 Dec 2015 IMF: increases support to Liberian economy following Ebola outbreak
http://www.publicfinanceinternational.org/news/2015/12/imf-increases-support-liberian-economy-following-ebola-outbreak
[The International Monetary Fund is to release a further USD10.2m to support the economy in Liberia following the impact of the Ebola virus outbreak and the decline in global commodity prices.]

